{"timestamp": "2025-12-01 13:25:13.443218", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\nNetwork: 2 bmv2 switches (switch_1, switch_2) and 2 hosts (host_1: 10.0.0.1, host_2: 10.0.0.2). Topology: host_1:eth0 <-> switch_1:eth0 ; host_2:eth0 <-> switch_2:eth0 ; switch_1:eth1 <-> switch_2:eth1. P4 program: bloom_filter.p4.\n\n1) Executive summary / health\n- The network is not healthy: host_1 and host_2 cannot exchange ICMP (100% packet loss in both tested directions).\n- Host network interfaces are up and link-detected, and bmv2 switches are receiving and processing packets; however frames are not being accepted by the destination host(s).\n- The most likely root cause is incorrect packet rewriting in the P4 pipeline: the switches are replacing the Ethernet destination address with a value derived from the IPv4 address (shown as 0a000001 / a000001 in logs) instead of a correct 6-byte destination MAC. As a result, the destination hosts do not see frames with their real MAC and drop them.\n\n2) Observed symptoms (concrete evidence)\n- Reachability tests:\n  - host_1 -> host_2: 4 transmitted, 0 received, 100% loss.\n  - host_2 -> host_1: 4 transmitted, 0 received, 100% loss.\n- Host interface state (host_1 and host_2):\n  - eth0 is UP, assigned 10.0.0.1/24 and 10.0.0.2/24 respectively.\n  - Both hosts show TX packets (pings sent) but RX packets = 0.\n  - ethtool on both eth0: Link detected: yes, speed 10000Mb/s, duplex full.\n- ARP/neighbor:\n  - ip neigh on both hosts show permanent neighbor entries: 10.0.0.2 -> 00:00:0a:00:00:02 and 10.0.0.1 -> 00:00:0a:00:00:01 (PERMANENT).\n- bmv2 switch logs (switch_1 and switch_2):\n  - switch logs show packets are received (e.g., \"Processing packet received on port 1\") and the ingress pipeline applies MyIngress.ipv4_lpm and selects MyIngress.ipv4_forward.\n  - The table/action entries shown in logs include entries like:\n    - MyIngress.ipv4_lpm: match 0a000001/32 -> Action MyIngress.ipv4_forward - a000001,2\n    - MyIngress.ipv4_lpm: match 0a000002/32 -> Action MyIngress.ipv4_forward - a000002,2  (similar)\n  - The forwarding action performs these primitives (from logs):\n    - hdr.ethernet.srcAddr = hdr.ethernet.dstAddr\n    - hdr.ethernet.dstAddr = dstAddr\n    - standard_metadata.egress_spec = port\n  - Repeated log lines: \"Transmitting packet of size 98 out of port 2\" — the switch is attempting to forward packets onward.\n- Additional log entries:\n  - \"JSON input file bloom_filter.json cannot be opened\" (present in switch logs).\n  - Some attempts to connect to Thrift clients returned \"Could not connect to thrift client on port 9090\" for certain operations.\n\n3) Localization — where the failure is occurring\n- Hosts:\n  - host_1 and host_2 network stacks are configured and interfaces are UP; both send packets (TX), but receive none (RX=0). The hosts themselves are not the primary fault.\n- Network fabric:\n  - Switches are receiving traffic from hosts and invoking forwarding logic (bmv2 logs confirm packet processing and egress).\n  - The forwarding logic on the bmv2 switches (the P4 program + table entries) is the likely failing component because the switches are rewriting Ethernet addresses in a way that appears inconsistent with the hosts’ MAC addresses.\n- Likely faulty components: P4 forwarding implementation (bloom_filter.p4) or the table entries deployed on the bmv2 switches (both switches show similar behavior, so likely both run the same faulty logic/config).\n\n4) Root-cause analysis (reasoned)\n- Symptom correlation:\n  - Packets reach the switch (switch logs show ingress and a subsequent \"Transmitting packet ... out of port X\").\n  - Hosts still receive nothing (host RX counters remain 0). This indicates frames transmitted by the switch do not match the destination host's expected MAC, or are otherwise malformed.\n- Direct evidence for wrong address rewriting:\n  - The forwarding action sets hdr.ethernet.dstAddr = dstAddr, where dstAddr logged in the table is the IPv4 address shown in hex (e.g., 0a000001 printed as a000001).\n  - That dstAddr corresponds to the IPv4 address (10.0.0.1 = 0a000001) rather than a full 6-byte Ethernet MAC (00:00:0a:00:00:01). If the switch writes a 32-bit IPv4 value into the 48-bit MAC field (or writes incorrectly-formed bytes), the resulting Ethernet destination will not match the actual host MAC, and the NIC on the destination host will drop the frame.\n- Additional supporting clues:\n  - The P4 code line numbers referenced in logs (bloom_filter.p4:164,167,173...) show the ethernet fields are explicitly being rewritten in the action. The exact logged values for dstAddr match the IPv4 addresses used for LPM matches (0a000001 etc.), confirming that the table/action parameter is an IP-derived value rather than a MAC.\n  - The message \"JSON input file bloom_filter.json cannot be opened\" suggests an optional runtime configuration (maybe MAC table or mapping) is missing; that could have caused the program to fall back to using IP values or defaults for the Ethernet destination parameter.\n- Therefore: The root cause is incorrect construction/assignment of Ethernet destination address in the P4 forwarding action (likely using IPv4 address value instead of the intended MAC, or wrong endianness/width when writing), causing frames forwarded by switches to carry an invalid/unmatched destination MAC and thus be dropped by destination hosts.\n\n5) Impact and scope\n- Functional: Host-to-host L3 connectivity (ICMP at least) is broken end-to-end; all forwarded traffic from one host to the other is being dropped at the final hop because of incorrect destination MAC.\n- Scope: Both switches exhibit the same forwarding behavior in logs; likely a systemic P4 program/configuration issue (deployed on both switches) rather than a single physical link outage.\n\n6) Relevant raw evidence excerpts (representative)\n- Ping: \"4 packets transmitted, 0 received, 100% packet loss\"\n- host ifconfig: eth0 TX packets 4 bytes 392 ; RX packets 0\n- ethtool: \"Link detected: yes\"\n- ip neigh: \"10.0.0.2 dev eth0 lladdr 00:00:0a:00:00:02 PERMANENT\"\n- bmv2 logs (example):\n  - Table entry dump: \"hdr.ipv4.dstAddr : LPM 0a000001/32 Action entry: MyIngress.ipv4_forward - a000001,2\"\n  - Actions executed: \"hdr.ethernet.srcAddr = hdr.ethernet.dstAddr\" ; \"hdr.ethernet.dstAddr = dstAddr\" ; \"Transmitting packet of size 98 out of port 2\"\n  - \"JSON input file bloom_filter.json cannot be opened\"\n\n7) Additional notes / possible secondary issues observed\n- Some Thrift client connections failed for table/counter operations (\"Could not connect to thrift client on port 9090\") — may be environmental and not essential to the forwarding failure, but worth noting.\n- The P4 program file bloom_filter.p4 is referenced in logs and action lines; attempts to cat *.p4 on the switch returned \"No such file or directory\" in this environment — may constrain on-switch debugging, but logs already point to problematic behavior.\n- Missing bloom_filter.json suggests runtime configuration that may have been expected by the P4 pipeline is absent.\n\n8) Suggested verification steps (to confirm root cause) — (no mitigations provided)\n- Inspect the exact value of ethernet.dstAddr in a packet as transmitted by the switch (capture on the switch->host link) and compare bytes to the destination host MAC.\n- Inspect P4 action parameter definitions and table entries to confirm whether the action parameter \"dstAddr\" is populated with an IPv4 value instead of a MAC or whether there is a width/endianness mismatch.\n- Check for the presence/contents of bloom_filter.json (the runtime configuration file referenced in logs) and whether it should supply MAC mapping information.\n\nSummary conclusion\n- Anomaly detected: end-to-end connectivity broken (100% packet loss).\n- Localization: problem lies in the bmv2 switch forwarding logic (P4 program + table entries) that rewrites Ethernet addresses.\n- Root cause: the P4 forwarding action is assigning an IP-derived value (0a000001 / a000002) to the Ethernet destination address (wrong format/width), producing frames whose destination MAC does not match the host NICs — therefore destination hosts drop the frames.\n\nIf you want, I can run targeted captures or additional commands (packet capture on switch interfaces, dump exact ethernet frames, or inspect the P4 action/table definitions) to further confirm byte-level mismatch and precisely show the incorrect ethernet.dstAddr bytes.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 20635, "output_tokens": 4345, "total_tokens": 24980, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 12032}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2304}}}
